import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Consultancy — grimbergIT">
  <article class="surface">
    <p class="eyebrow">Engagements</p>
    <h1>Consultancy</h1>

    <p>
      Teams engage me when their quality practice can no longer keep up with the pace at which they
      want to ship. I help them close that gap without turning testing into a bottleneck or a
      ceremony.
    </p>

    <h2>What I focus on</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Quality strategy.</strong> Most teams don't have a testing problem; they have a confidence
      problem. Together we untangle testing from release theatre and rebuild it around the signals that
      actually predict how the system behaves in production. The output is a strategy the team can defend
      on its own — fewer green checkmarks, more clarity about what each layer of testing is for.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Test automation that lasts.</strong> Automation is only cheap the first time you write it.
      I work with teams on suites shaped like a pyramid rather than an ice-cream cone: fast where they
      can be, focused where they must be, tied closely to the code they protect. The measure of success
      is a suite that survives a refactor without becoming the reason a refactor doesn't happen.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Delivery-flow platform work.</strong> Quality lives outside the test files too — in the
      pipelines that ship changes, the environments where they run, and the observability that tells the
      team what happened. I help teams make that path predictable: shorter feedback loops, sharper signals,
      less time spent guessing whether the last deploy went well.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Developer experience.</strong> Software gets shipped by people who can stay in flow, and
      flow is fragile. I help teams surface the small frictions that erode focus — slow builds, ambiguous
      errors, environment drift, half-finished internal tools — and address them one at a time, starting
      with the ones costing the most hours per week. The measure is that engineers spend more of their
      day on the work itself, and less on the space around it.
    </p>

    <h2>How I work</h2>

    <p>
      Engagements are short by design — typically two to six weeks. Anything longer, and the team
      starts leaning on me instead of learning from me.
    </p>

    <p>
      I embed with engineers — pairing on real code, sitting in real standups, reviewing real pull
      requests — because that's where change actually takes root. When it's useful, I also work with
      the executive layer, to make sure the team's direction is one their leaders are willing to
      back. Slide decks are optional, and rarely necessary.
    </p>

    <p>
      Whatever I learn during an engagement is written down — decisions, trade-offs, the reasoning
      behind them — so the team keeps the thinking after I leave. If the notes wouldn't be useful to
      the person who joins next month, they weren't worth writing.
    </p>

    <p><a href="/contact">Start the conversation →</a></p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
